Tau and density (private link)

Description

Data for the investigation of tau geometry and the electron density

Examples: a residue that fails the density test and a residue that passes with outlier at 0.2. It is clear the atoms' electron density is evidential for the outlier but not for the residue that fails.

Best Supported Dataset

A dataset is obtained from ultrahigh-resolution xray crystallographic structures that will have sufficient experimental evidence to inspect and validate all tau variation against the electron density.

The set is first created from pdbs <1A non-homologous at 90% with >40 residues.

From this only residues with no multiple occupants are accepted. A further restriction is put on the bfactor of a residue to be no more than 1.3x the average bfactor of the structure.

Further restrictions are then made to create 5 candidate sets. Eact atom point from the pdb is checked to see if it is a maximum.
It must first pass the hessian eigenvalue maximumm test of 3 -ve eigenvalues.
Then a cube is built around it and every vertex checked. If any are greater then it fails the maximum test.
The grid points are fractions of a crs cube at 0.2, 0.25, 0.3, 0.4 and 0.5 (no data found at 0.1).

A statistical comparison is done of all the sets - all the sets have very similar means and sds though differing counts:
(NCACO_B02 means atoms of the type N, CA,C or O are guaranteed to be a maximum within 0.2 of a grid point)

  • Set NCACO_B02 has 3,796 residues
  • Set NCACO_B025 has 16,388 residues
  • Set NCACO_B03 has 30,870 residues
  • Set NCACO_B04 has 47,797 residues
  • Set NCACO_B05 has 54,241 residues

    • Categorisation

    This has been done using radiant images to cluster the different pictures, then describe thos geometrically

    Currently this is in very early stages of definition as follows:

  • Category A1The oxygen 2 residues back is the closest oxygen to the nitrogen
  • Category C1The nearest oxygen to the nitrogen is < 3.6A, the dihdral it makes with tau is near planar and it is on the right
  • Category D1The nearest oxygen is <3.6A away and the dihedral with N+1 is near planar
  • Category E2The nearest oxygen is <3.6A but not planar
  • Category XEverything else

    • Electron density of the categories

    Categories based on psi/tau/N:N+1 are invented that attempt to split the values up into logical groups.

    Taking a selection of residues at the most extreme tau ends in the best supported categories, the electron density is visualised for supporting evidence of the accuracy of the pdb tau calculation. The possible causes of variation on the tau angle can be inspected by the seperation into these categories.

    • Category 1: Long N:N+1 and psi near +/- 180
    • Category 2: Between values: -100< PSI <100 with N:N+1 between 3-3.4A
    • Category 3: PSI near 0,the bottom of the curve, tau<114
    • Category 4: PSI=0, Shortest N:N+1 < 2.8 at tau > 114
    • Category 5: PSI near 0, 2.8 < N:N+1 < 3 at tau > 114
    • Category 6: Psi=0, N:N+1 > 2.8

    At the end of each set of visualised electron density data, an average image is created - this gives some idea of the differences between the categories.
